column1: Before 31 December 2019, will a Model 3 produced in Tesla's Shanghai Gigafactory 3 be delivered to a customer?
column6: ['Technology']
This one came very close. https://www.reuters.com/article/us-tesla-china-delivery/tesla-delivers-first-china-made-model-3-sedans-in-just-under-a-year-idUSKBN1YY04E
Per others... https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2019/dec/30/tesla-delivers-first-china-made-cars-from-shanghai-factory
Looks like a done deal: https://twitter.com/teslacn/status/1211458539329187842
https://electrek.co/2019/12/27/tesla-start-made-in-china-model-3-deliveries/
Per other forecasters - 15 will be delivered to employees Dec 30 https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a30344470/tesla-delivers-first-china-model-3-cars/
I think that there is no great risk in increasing it to 100%, same logic as:
the headlines are that they will begin delivery on Dec 30th!
Why not?
"Gone fishin' " - D Cheney
"You gotta know when to hold em... When to fold em Know when to walk away.... Know when to run!"
https://www.reuters.com/article/us-tesla-china/tesla-set-to-begin-deliveries-of-china-made-model-3-cars-on-dec-30-idUSKBN1YV0MB
https://www.cnbc.com/2019/12/27/tesla-set-to-begin-deliveries-of-china-made-model-3-cars-on-dec-30.html

It does not hurt to increase the probability further: though Chinese news only say that the first 15 cars will be delivered to factory workers [1] (without indicating if they are technically customers), the English news phrase it differently, saying that the first 15 customers to receive a car will be factory workers [2]. This increases the probability of a "yes" resolution to the question.
They just announced firm plans to deliver a few on the 30th

According to [1], deliveries will begin next week. In particular "在上海工厂生产的首批15辆Model 3轿车将于12月30日开始向员工交付", which means: "the first 15 Model 3 cars produced in the Shanghai factory will be delivered to workers on 30th December".

Reducing my estimate upon further research. On the one hand, it looks like at least 1,000 MIC Model 3s have been produced already. There are literally pictures of them posted at sites like tesmanian.com. So it's getting to the point where it's going to be hard *not* to have at least a handful of them delivered.

Reducing the probability a bit farther, as there are not so many days left. Apparently [1] (which is repeated in many other Chinese news) from yesterday it has been circulating some rumors that the first few Model 3 will be delivered as a Christmas present (which would indicate a delivery in the next few days). The rumors are derived from some Christmas image by Tesla. Yet this is contrasted with the official estimates of deliveries starting at the beginning of January.
Changing my estimate again, based on what Tesla China is saying

For the moment it is difficult to know what is going to happen: on 17th of December, there were the news [1] that within one week Tesla technicians will contact the customers to install chargers at their homes/garages and then decide on a date for the delivery of the Model 3. More recent news talk either of deliveries expected to happen by the end of the standard year ("国产Model 3预计年低开始交付", i.e. "the delivery of the locally produced model 3 is expected to begin by the end of the year") [2] or before the Chinese new year. Besides we all have seen all these pictures of trucks going outside of Gigafactory 3 with model 3's.

I have lost my nerve. The cars are available in quanitity, but abilty to sell may target a certain future date not in 2019. If they were able to sell, they would have surely done so by now. Wheter its licensing or back office mechanisms, it would appear to have the same impact - no sales booked yet. Perhaps I'll regret this change. :-)

I still think it's more likely than not, but I am lowering my estimate a bit here, based on there being only 7 days left before the 31st. Given the announcement today of huge new financing from local Chinese banks, it's not too likely there are undue delays: https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-12-23/tesla-secures-more-than-1-4-billion-in-financing-from-china?utm_content=business&utm_source=twitter&utm_medium=social&cmpid=socialflow-twitter-business&utm_campaign=socialflow-organic

This time I am increasing the probability again, from 75 to 80% percent. Apparently, on the 17th of December it was reported [1] that some customers received a notice announcing a few details about their locally produced model 3 in a week (特斯拉送货专家将在通知发出后一周内与Model 3车主联系: "a delivery specialist from Tesla will contact you owner of a model 3 within one week". Then later it explains the things this guy will do, which include installing a charger at the home of the owner. The final point is: 车辆交付地点和日期, "setting a place and a date for the car delivery").
This question has moved from 'can they?' to 'would they?' My guess is that timing has to do with marketing impact, long-term, and Chinese spending habits, short-term
I will reduce the probability as there are only two weeks left before the end of the year: everything is pointing towards a first delivery really soon, but the timing will be decided by Tesla.
Still possible, they seem very close but there isn't much time left.
I'll stand pat, and maybe fall flat, but this quote from Telarati Dec 16 gives me some hope.

I will slightly increase the probability in view of the latest news [1,2,3]: according to [1] Tesla might have received the sales permit (yet this is an inference, there is no direct confirmation, and this piece of news points out that the inference comes from non-Chinese media, probably Teslarati). According to [2], Gigafactory 3 can already produce 1000 vehicles per week. According to [3], trucks loaded with Model 3's have been spotted in their way to Tesla shops or maybe for delivery to customers (it shows some pics).
Got this e-mail today.

Minimal threshold to make this a 'yes' -- Tesla delivery during the US holiday season provides a positive publicity narrative -- verification of a 'yes' may be the more difficult prospect -- https://insideevs.com/news/386812/china-made-tesla-model-3-deliveries-imminent/

Continue to be challenged in this one. They have approval to sell now. Tesla itself only says January. They need a number of vehicles for testing and publicity (not sale). There’s also the question of actual delivery which is often done when there’s a certain volume built up. Three weeks left. Low threshold to resolution (1 delivery resolves).
https://www.tesmanian.com/blogs/tesmanian-blog/tesla-received-permit-to-sell-and-deliver-china-made-model-3-to-customer
Tesla received their permit to sell in China, and previous estimate for deliveries to begin in January could be moved up.
https://mspoweruser.com/tesla-china-sale-start/
Getting close! https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-mic-model-3-first-customer-deliveries-transport-carriers/

"The latest drone flyover video of Gigafactory shows over 200 Model 3 vehicles parked in a lot at the back of the factory."[1] How long will it take for a delivery take after sales approval? Next day?

Generally looks good, but there are still two risks: 1) Tesla has often been less reliable than they claimed to be and 2) cars are complex things to build. They might be almost ready, but some things might be missing (including the logistics to actually get the first car to a customer).
I am lowering again the probability, though in earnest I am not sure in which direction to correct.
Production has started and more than 100 have been produced to date - the process to get permission to deliver still needs to be completed.

Deadline is closing without an announcement/delivery and with the revealing of their new cybertruck I'm more convinced the company will be more focused on the fallout of this reveal in the final month of the year.

For the moment I am reducing the probability: the deliveries are not expected to happen till beginning of next year. According to [1] the first one might happen before Chinese new year (twenty something of January).
https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-11-21/tesla-aims-to-deliver-made-in-china-cars-before-late-january

Per others we are really discussing whether low threshold of 1 car delivery in next 5,5 weeks will happen. Sounds like bulk deliveries may not happen until Jan (not relevant to question resolution). From Bloomberg... “ The deliveries would come from the first batch of cars that Tesla produces in bulk later this year — not the test vehicles that the company has been manufacturing in small quantities recently. Tesla said in October that it expected to begin deliveries to customers in the first quarter but didn’t specify which month.” https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-made-in-china-model-3-local-stores-nov-22/ https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-11-21/tesla-aims-to-deliver-made-in-china-cars-before-late-january https://www.irishtimes.com/business/transport-and-tourism/tesla-planning-to-deliver-made-in-china-model-3-by-end-of-january-1.4090808 https://insideevs.com/news/383636/tesla-china-made-model-3-deliveries/
Lot of news buzz. They're either ALL shit financial/business journalists or they've got shares in Tesla. Elon doesn't really fail tbh other than on Twitter.
Why did China withdraw subsidies? Good chance to hurt Tesla. Delay in licensure arbitrary time period. .....
Raising due to Tesla obtaining manufacturing license [1]. Reports of 17k Model 3s from Gigafactory 3 by end of the year [2].
Research by @ManuPV (HT) suggests that deliveries are imminent [1]
Updating again - a lesson not too try to do too many things at once.

Actually, I am now realizing the Long range and Performance models don't seem to be Made in China ones. Under the Standard version it clearly says "Made in China" but it doesn't under the other two options....
Going back up. Previously I had gone to 45% because of reports that Tesla's own estimated delivery time for Made in China models is Beginning of 2020. [1]

Per @Emil and . Approval for mass production granted . Approval for local sale outstanding . Increased number pre prod vehicles including testing and meet/greet . Chinese builds benefitted from lessons learned in US (supposedly better build quality?) https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-gigafactory-3-gets-model-3-mass-production-license/
Tesla seems to be planning delivery in 2020.

Reasons: 1) First 6 imported Model 3 were delivered to Chinese mainland customers on 22/02/2019, which is slightly earlier than previous time estimation of March, 2019 by Telsa. 2) According to Telsa's Weibo, customers can make resveration for Model 3 from Shanghai Gigafactory from 25/10/2019, and estimation of delivery is Q1, 2020. 3) I therefore gave 9% in case Telsa continue to surprise Chinese customers.
Raising from 65% on latest news.

Elon likes to show off, and show that he can accomplish things large enterprises achieve but faster, cheaper, and better. He has on several occasions on twitter bragged about how fast tesla is, and his other companies.

Per other forecasters... @Emil. @ManuPV. Coming down slightly. It’s normal to stockpile autos for bulk deliveries. But also possible early versions will be gifted to local officials (don’t know if that counts as delivery).

I will decrease the probability a bit in this update, in [1] we read "根据中国国标的续航里程目前还在评估实验中" which means something like "according to (certain) government agency for standards for journey endurance it is still under testing", sorry for the really crappy translation as I don't even know how that agency is called in English and what type of certification are they trying to get. In the same source they say this thing about "预计在2020年第一季度开始正式交付", i.e. "estimations are that official deliveries will happen in Q1 2020".
The timeline has been delayed as Tesla is waiting for an additional government approval.
Lowering down to 90% given uncertainty on government approval for Tesla to begin mass production. Rumors of event on November 11th so will update based on that news.

Californian electric car maker Tesla will commence making its Model 3 electric sedan at its new Shanghai Gigafactory in China on November 11, according to reports emerging in China today. https://thedriven.io/2019/11/07/reports-emerge-of-tesla-model-3-production-date-in-shanghai-and-catl-battery-deal/
The news report indicates Tesla is yet to get a manufacturing certificate. Tesla claims it is on target to get it at the end of the year.

ccording to the image Tesla China released, it expects to deliver Model 3’s made in Gigafactory 3 by Q1 2020, which means that reservation holders can expect their vehicles between January and March next year. https://www.tesmanian.com/blogs/tesmanian-blog/tesla-china-model-3-delivery-date-special-badge?_pos=13&_sid=423e42fa5&_ss=r
When will I got married
Who will be my future husband, what is his name
Will I Make it in life

Often some of the newest models off a line go to press pool and/or are given to local dignitaries like mayors. I’m still thinking it would be a positive symbolic gesture (and good publicity) to deliver a few before Western year end (and more by Jan 25 - Chinese New Year).

Tesla is slightly ahead of schedule as at 27/10/2019, having already begun the production of the Model 3 before November. The facility is the fastest built Tesla factory to date, having taken less than a year. This may be attributed to the cheaper workforce combined with the previous experience building the USA factories, streamlining the process. It is also reported that cooperation of the Chinese government helped the process. Hence we can expect the delivery of the Chinese Model 3 from the completion of the Chinese factory to be faster than its US counterpart from the completion of the US factory.

The company told investors Wednesday that Tesla's (TSLA) new Gigafactory in Shanghai started trial production "ahead of schedule" this month and is building "full vehicles, from body to paint to general assembly." https://edition.cnn.com/2019/10/24/tech/tesla-gigafactory-china-europe/index.html

Tesla's recent quarterly call indicates Gigafactory 3 has begun assembly of Model 3s. If it is indeed true that the first set of cars will be sold to employees, which counts as delivery, then the probability of delivery has increased.
I will increase the probability from 97 to 98 percent. There a few factors to consider:
Before 31 December 2019, will a Model 3 produced in Tesla's Shanghai Gigafactory 3 be delivered to a customer? This has got to be great motivation for theShanghai team - they'll do it handily.
Only have to produce one vehicle and have one employee drive it home.
Tesla has approval to begin production and is expected to start in the next few weeks.

Tesla was just given the OK from China to start building electric vehicles in its newly constructed plant outside Shanghai. The factory, called Gigafactory 3, will produce at least 1000 Model 3 electric cars a week, according to Tesla. Production could commence within several weeks, the company said. https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a29505737/tesla-gigafactory-china-model-3-production/
“Could start building them any time now”. Ten weeks to deliver something...seems likely https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a29505737/tesla-gigafactory-china-model-3-production/
Completing the factory does not mean car is delivered to a customer.

https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-tesla/tesla-gets-approval-to-start-manufacturing-in-china-idUSKBN1WW0NM This is the official gummint okey-dokey, and the factory seems ready to go. Under the terms of this Q they don't need to meet their announced targets, which they never do, but only to crank out one vehicle and deliver it to somebody. Probably even Musk can't screw this up now, but keeping this at only 99% because Tesla has snatched defeat from the jaws of victory so often in the past.
Chinese Government permit to run Tesla's Shanghai plant was granted.
Because China is good at fast ramping but Tesla is not good at delivering to commitment
Tesla has never made one single deadline. Ever.
Yes. It will be symbolic. But production will be accomplished.
Tesla has a history of underperformance however a higher probability of at least one car being delivered for marketing.
Tesla Model 3 (made-in-China?) spotted on new Gigafactory 3 test track https://electrek.co/2019/10/07/tesla-model-3-made-in-china-gigafactory-3-test-track/
Before the end of a decade this would be a very large ceremonial milestone that both China and Tesla will want to see happen

I'm increasing a 2% (from 95 to 97%) in view of the latest new in Sina: "特斯拉Model 3现身上海工厂测试跑道 投产指日可待?" ("Apparently, there has been a test in a runway of a Tesla 3 in the Shanghai factory. Is production imminent?") [1] The news show a picture of a Model 3 in a track outside the factory (but it also points out that "但动力系统的生产是否准备就绪还不清楚", i.e. "It is not clear whether the production of the mechanical systems are ready yet").
Fastest way to increase overall production numbers is to start production in a new factory, vs. organic growth in existing factories. And growth is needed to make the numbers add up. Not easy to do.

Elon Musk has been notorious of very aggressive timeline. I would have said lesss than 50%. But based based on current progress it seems quite probable and I am forced to increase chances to 75%. For it to start delivering in Q1 2020 is 95%

The quality manufacturing of any electro-mechanical product is typically fraught with uncertainty. From the hiring of qualified personnel, the production of prototypes, the assimilation of quality management systems etc.; the latter 20% of the GF3 project could take as much as 80% of the allotted time. For a factory that was originally scheduled to begin production in March 2020, it is unlikely, impractical and unnecessary for Tesla to push its completion schedule.
New "leaked" images from Tesla Giga 3 https://insideevs.com/news/374439/leaked-tesla-gigafactory-3-several-model-3/amp/

Weak 3Q19 TSLA delivery report places further pressure on Tesla and Musk to reinvigorate the growth narrative. Hyping the China narrative is quickly becoming the top priority. Tesla is currently shipping cars to China. Reports suggest the company expects to be "producing" 1,000 cars per week there by the end of the year. This is highly unlikely, and it is very likely they will "produce" some cars.
Going a few points higher because the factory seems to be is producing cars with a rumored delivery date sometime in November.
As other's have mentioned, news is coming out the production will begin mid October. Baring a disaster, a car will be produced by the factory.

https://www.reuters.com/article/us-tesla-china-shanghai-plant/teslas-china-production-to-start-eyes-on-mass-production-timing-sources-idUSKBN1WH0HN Despite Tesla's history of egregious overpromising, if they are starting production now and only have to crank out one vehicle by year end, the odds are pretty good. They will not of course meet their announced targets, but that's not the question here.

InsideEV's just put out their estimate of 3Q US deliveries for Tesla. U.S. units are expected to be down y/y and Q/Q, despite lower Average Selling Prices. The quarter will bring higher foreign sales particularly in the Netherlands where tax incentives are expiring soon. The growth story keeping TSLA stock up is looking more tenuous and pumping their China potential will be important to keep the growth narrative alive. As such, by whatever means necessary Elon Musk will deliver a Model 3 "built" in Shanghai.
I rise the probability from 90 to 95%, the reasons are:

Musk and his Tesla contingency appear motivated to ignite global change via clean energy and elimination of carbon emissions. He's bold, occasionally overtly brash, but he values innovation, ingenuity, progress and perhaps most vitally, action. Without an obvious roadblock (pun intended) deterring the Gigafactory from moving forward it would seem they are exceeding timeline expectations, potentially priming the Tesla brand for an emphatic global statement: 'we do it better...and we can act faster.' Test production of a Model 3 has succeeded and expectancy of mass production has accelerated to a 10/14 estimate. With the world watching Chinese economics very closely, this an opportunity for both Musk, and China to seize hold of a vital market. Neither is likely to disappoint. Leaving 10% of wiggle room for the unforeseen. Confidence in Tesla's success rises every day.
Tesla seems to have turned a corner and I believe with the industry's eyes on Shanghai, the contingent there is working doubly hard to ensure the above deadline is met.
https://electrek.co/2019/09/26/tesla-model-3-body-in-white-gigafactory-3-production-start-oct-14/

Yesterday it was claimed that by 14th of October production in Gigafactory 3 will begin [1]. Now according to 東方財富 (East money) [2] the first Model 3 will be delivered to customers before the end of the year (首辆白车身已经下线，预计今年年底前首辆国产Model 3可以交付: the first body-in-white has already been produced, the estimation is that by the end of this year it will be possible to deliver the first Model 3).

Per @Emil - factory passed inspection. Small scale production in Q4 to work through processes. Still a bit of a crapshoot re customer delivery. Perhaps early models given to VIP’s and influencers. Perhaps Chinese will deliver on some of Musk’s targets... https://www.cnbc.com/2019/09/18/tesla-model-3s-are-big-sellers-in-china-jl-warren-q3-tesla-update.html

Going to temporarily rise the probability another 10% at least: apparently, the Lingang Group (the guys in charge for the area in which Gigafactory 3 is located, i.e. basically the Chinese Government) anticipates mass production of the Model 3 for the 14th of October. The Chinese tend to end up doing things even before schedule.

Today Teslarati has reported that Gigafactory 3 has rolled out the first body-in-white (BIW). I am not totally sure, but seems a good signal. Thus I increase the probability by an additional 3% (from 72 to 75%).
Seems the factory is producing cars with a rumored delivery date sometime in November.

From the news in Teslarati, the first pre-orders were made in May and they are expected to be delivered in 6-10 months, where 50% of this range is within the present year. It happens that the factory is being completed faster than expected, the 6-10 months could mean that a few pre-orders will be delivered in 6 months and the last pre-orders in 10 months, giving a larger than 50% probability. I would say at least 2/3, which I would scale up owing to the recent news of Tesla hiring more people for Gigafactory 3 (I would add a 5% to the 67%).
@Emil 's comments in [1] and additional (if slightly sensationalist) reports that the start of production has already happened or is immanent [2].
Musk says this will happen, ergo it won't. More likely next Spring. Stay tuned.
Tesla guidance has suggested a start of production in early Q4, suggesting plenty of runway so to speak for this question to resolve as a 'yes' if their guidance turns out too optimistic. [1]
